---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const title = "Beginner's Guide to Fitness Nutrition | SmartFitCalc";
const description =
    "Everything beginners need to know about fitness nutrition - from protein timing to meal planning fundamentals.";

const articleStructuredData = {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    headline: "Beginner's Guide to Fitness Nutrition",
    description: description,
    datePublished: "2024-12-01",
    dateModified: "2025-12-28",
    author: {
        "@type": "Organization",
        name: "SmartFitCalc",
        url: "https://smartfitcalc.com",
    },
    publisher: {
        "@type": "Organization",
        name: "SmartFitCalc",
        url: "https://smartfitcalc.com",
        logo: {
            "@type": "ImageObject",
            url: "https://smartfitcalc.com/favicon.svg",
        },
    },
    mainEntityOfPage: {
        "@type": "WebPage",
        "@id": "https://smartfitcalc.com/blog/fitness-nutrition-beginners",
    },
};
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
    <script
        type="application/ld+json"
        set:html={JSON.stringify(articleStructuredData)}
    />
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
        <header class="mb-10 text-center">
            <a href="/blog" class="text-sm text-primary-600 hover:underline"
                >← Back to Blog</a
            >
            <h1 class="mt-4 mb-4 text-4xl font-extrabold text-gray-800">
                Beginner's Guide to Fitness Nutrition
            </h1>
            <div class="text-gray-500 text-sm">December 2024 • 8 min read</div>
        </header>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-gray-600">
            <p class="lead text-xl">
                You can't out-train a bad diet. Whether you want to lose fat,
                build muscle, or improve performance, nutrition is the
                foundation. Here's everything a beginner needs to know.
            </p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                The Fundamentals: Calories and Macros
            </h2>
            <p>
                All nutrition boils down to two concepts: <strong
                    >calories</strong
                > (total energy) and <strong>macros</strong> (protein, carbs, fat).
                Master these basics, and you're 90% of the way there.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Calories</strong> = Weight change (deficit = lose, surplus
                    = gain)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Protein</strong> = Muscle building and repair</li>
                <li><strong>Carbs</strong> = Workout fuel and recovery</li>
                <li><strong>Fats</strong> = Hormones and overall health</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Protein: The MVP
            </h2>
            <p>
                If you only focus on one thing, make it protein. It builds
                muscle, keeps you full, and preserves muscle when dieting. Aim
                for:
            </p>
            <div class="rounded-xl bg-red-50 p-4 my-4 border border-red-100">
                <p class="font-bold text-red-800">
                    1.6 - 2.2 grams per kg of body weight
                </p>
                <p class="text-red-700 text-sm mt-1">
                    Spread across 3-4 meals for optimal absorption
                </p>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-700 mt-4">
                Best protein sources:
            </h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Chicken, turkey, lean beef</li>
                <li>Fish and seafood</li>
                <li>Eggs and egg whites</li>
                <li>Greek yogurt and cottage cheese</li>
                <li>Whey or plant protein powder</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Meal Timing: Does It Matter?
            </h2>
            <p>
                For most people, <strong
                    >total daily intake matters more than timing</strong
                >. However, some basic principles help:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Eat protein within a few hours of training</li>
                <li>
                    Don't train completely fasted if building muscle is the goal
                </li>
                <li>
                    Spread protein across meals rather than one huge serving
                </li>
                <li>Carbs around workouts can improve performance</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Pre and Post Workout Nutrition
            </h2>
            <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 my-4">
                <div class="rounded-xl bg-blue-50 p-4 border border-blue-100">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-blue-800 mb-2">
                        Pre-Workout (1-2 hrs before)
                    </h4>
                    <ul class="text-blue-700 text-sm space-y-1">
                        <li>Moderate carbs for energy</li>
                        <li>Moderate protein</li>
                        <li>Low fat (digests slowly)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="rounded-xl bg-green-50 p-4 border border-green-100">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-green-800 mb-2">
                        Post-Workout (within 2 hrs)
                    </h4>
                    <ul class="text-green-700 text-sm space-y-1">
                        <li>Protein for muscle repair</li>
                        <li>Carbs to replenish glycogen</li>
                        <li>A regular meal works fine</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Hydration Basics
            </h2>
            <p>Even mild dehydration impacts performance. Aim for:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>~30-40ml per kg of body weight daily</li>
                <li>Extra 500-1000ml for workouts</li>
                <li>Urine should be pale yellow</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Simple Meal Planning Tips
            </h2>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <strong>Build plates around protein</strong> - Start with a protein
                    source, add everything else
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Prep in batches</strong> - Cook protein and carbs for
                    3-4 days at once
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Keep it simple</strong> - Rotating between 4-5 meals you
                    enjoy is easier than variety
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Stock the essentials</strong> - Eggs, chicken, rice, oats,
                    vegetables, and fruit
                </li>
            </ol>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                Supplements: What's Actually Worth It
            </h2>
            <p>Most supplements are unnecessary. The few that have evidence:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Protein powder:</strong> Convenient, not magical
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Creatine:</strong> Well-researched for strength/muscle
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Vitamin D:</strong> If you're deficient (most are)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Caffeine:</strong> Proven performance enhancer</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mt-8 mb-4">
                The Bottom Line
            </h2>
            <p>
                Don't overcomplicate it. Eat enough protein, control your
                calories based on your goal, eat mostly whole foods, stay
                hydrated, and be consistent. That's 95% of the battle.
            </p>

            <p class="mt-8">
                Ready to dial in your nutrition? <a
                    href="/macro-calculator"
                    class="text-primary-600 hover:underline font-medium"
                    >Calculate your macros →</a
                >
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-gray-200">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
            <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
                <a
                    href="/blog/calculate-macros-weight-loss"
                    class="block rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-4 hover:border-primary-300"
                >
                    <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800">
                        Calculate Macros for Weight Loss
                    </h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
                        Step-by-step macro setup
                    </p>
                </a>
                <a
                    href="/blog/understanding-tdee"
                    class="block rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-4 hover:border-primary-300"
                >
                    <h4 class="font-medium text-gray-800">
                        Understanding TDEE
                    </h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">
                        Finding your calorie needs
                    </p>
                </a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </article>
</BaseLayout>
